answers.body_markdown:
This is a very low-level way to read a text file. The method `read` that you used [returns](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/io/Reader.html#read(char%5B%5D)) the number of read characters and you can print them, say, in a loop:

```java
int n = reader.read(array);

for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
	System.out.print(array[i]);
}
```

Or you can [create](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#%3Cinit%3E(char%5B%5D,int,int)) a new `String` from the read portion of the array:

```java
int n = reader.read(array);
System.out.println(new String(array, 0, n));
```

`System.out` is of class `PrintStream`, which is rather ancient. The newer class `PrintWriter` has a [method](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/io/PrintWriter.html#write(char%5B%5D,int,int)) to write a part of an array:

```java
int n = reader.read(array);
PrintWriter writer = new PrintWriter(System.out);
writer.write(array, 0, n);
writer.flush();
```

Unfortunately, if the text file is empty, `n` becomes `-1` and two last approaches will fail, so for that an extra check is required.

Note that you read only first 100 characters of the file this way. If the file can be larger, you need to repeat reading in a `while` loop.

For more high-level operations with text files, use [`BufferedReader`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/io/BufferedReader.html) class (contains a handy method `readLine`) or [`Scanner`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Scanner.html).

